INSERT INTO `wp_a55jrcpgkb_posts` VALUES("358", "4", "2017-01-10 17:57:47", "2017-01-11 00:57:47", "<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Medicine is the science or practice of the diagnosis, treatment, and prevention of disease</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. Doctors have great medical minds and are trained and licensed to treat sick and injured people. These Merriam-Webster definitions depicts what humans believe to be a doctors purpose. Meanwhile, death, by the very same dictionary, is defined as the ruin or destruction of something. The definitions of medicine and doctor have changed minimally over time. The definition of death, on the other hand, is one that reflects the modern attitude toward death, which incorporates aspects of Western and Judeo-Christian culture. With the advances in science and medicine, humans have become accustomed to taking advantage of the medical tools at their disposal, giving themselves a chance to extend their lives as much as possible. As a result, when death occurs, it is unexpected and disappointing to the family, the patient, and even the doctor. The process of death and dying in modern times places an economic burden on taxpayers and families. End of life care accounts for a sizable portion of our healthcare spending, which puts pressure on the government and grieving families. The culture and stigma in the United States surrounding death and dying is not only dangerous but unsustainable for Americans.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Death, as a construct, is scary. After all, a person that you may have known forever can vanish within a second. Yet, this construct of death is relatively new. In the past, death was much more foreseen and normalized. A national study looking into the perceptions of dying concluded that in the past and in eastern cultures, since death was much more predictable, it wasnt as threatening of a concept (5). With the shift towards chronic disease rather than infectious diseases and the rise of medicine and antibiotics, the idea that death is a part of life has become some sort of taboo. This stigma that is attached to death and dying remains because many believe that death will and can be delayed. Alongside the silent killers like heart disease, there are usually immediate causes of death that can be treated via medicine, which prolongs the death process. In Atul Gawandes book, Being Mortal, the slow killer is retinal disease, which was experienced by Bella, the geriatricians (Felix) wife. Felix had to retire from his job and completely support Bella after she went completely blind. As she continued to age, Bella lost large chunks of her memory and hearing. The quality of her life deteriorated to the point where Atul Gawande dared us to answer if it was even worth it for her to continue living like this (1). This pattern in medicine only results in spending large portions of a patients final year in the hospital circling the drain with low quality of life instead of spending time with their family at home. This pattern leads to another reason of why humans fear death more than they did in the past. In the duration of history, most deaths occurred at home (6). This means that relatives and family members were exposed to the experience of caring for dying people, which enabled them to have a first-hand experience with the dying process. </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">As a result, although death may have been just as tragic as it is today, it was also seen as more normal than the perception of death in more modern times. Since new therapeutic trials continue to flash in headlines and miracle cases are always trending, the American population has this notion of invincibility embedded into their thoughts (3). Thus, when death is imminent, people are more willing to try drastic, high-risk, low-reward measures which often yield in unfortunate circumstances. Unfortunately, these tactics place an economic strain on citizens, hospitals, and the government.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The healthcare system in America is tough for even the best hospitals, and the worst is yet to come as costs continue to rise and the baby boomer generation continues to age. End-of-life care is among some of the costliest government expenditures. On average, Medicare paid about $26,000 on average for the last year of a persons life. In fact, end-of-life care allots for approximately 10 to 12% of total healthcare spending (4). This type of spending begs us to ask a question: why is so much money going into end-of-life care spending? Objectively speaking, about 10% of taxpayer dollars in the healthcare sector is washed down the drain in end of life care since the patients life ends within a year anyway. The current Medicare system in the US is unsustainable and makes it almost impossible to continue practicing medicine this way (4). </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Currently, there are 34.8 million Americans that are above the age of 65. This figure will double by 2050 to about 72.2 million. On top of that, there will be an expected 240% increase in the 85-plus population (2). With this increased dependency ratio and newfound dependence on the working class supporting their elders, it is simply economically unfeasible to expect our taxpayers pick up the tab for this populations Medicare and insurance. It would require drastic tax hikes and would put much pressure on those who are employed to produce for the those who have low survival chances (4).</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">These expenses dont even factor in what the family must contribute for the medical bills. Although Medicare does cover many aspects of healthcare, there are many treatments and drugs that are unreasonably expensive, even for people with coverage (3). Families are responsible for paying their share, which could be thousands of dollars in medical bills, even if the treatment doesnt work and this could end up being money flushed down the toilet (3). A possible solution that balances longevity of life while being economically practical could be cutting off benefits after they reach the average age of death in the country. For example, if a senior citizen was possibly getting Medicare, she would get the full benefits of Medicare until the age of 78, which is the average death of an America. After that, she would still receive coverage, however, there would be more limitations to prevent the waste of money. Although in an ideal world, it would be incredible for no one to die, it is not realistic and this train of thought can prove to be harmful to everyone. </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Spending loads of taxpayer money for end-of-life care should not be necessary and massive reform must occur to address unsustainable culture of Americas healthcare system.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Although Merriam Webster defines death as the ruin or destruction of something, it has become evident that this definition needs a reboot, which would also call for the restructuring of an entire culture. Whether it be due to the immediateness of death or the emotions attached to death and dying, the concept of death needs to be redefined, particularly in America. While other cultures have accepted or even celebrated death, Western culture has treated death like a taboo, despite it being something that every human being on this planet will go through. With the unfeasible culture of end-of-life care spending and the emotional withdrawal attached to dying, we can no longer afford this definition of death. If there was one phrase that I took from reading Being Mortal, it was this: In the end, people dont view their life as merely the average of all of its moments- which, after all, is mostly nothing much plus some sleep. For human beings, life is meaningful because it is a story. A story has a sense of a whole, and its arc is determined by the significant moments, the ones where something happens. The definition of death is no longer the ruin or destruction of something; in reality, its simply the last phase of the life cycle, one that helps write the conclusion to a humans story.</span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;", "Death Magnified", "", "publish", "open", "open", "", "death-magnified", "", "", "2017-01-17 15:52:31", "2017-01-17 22:52:31", "", "0", "http://hopkinsmedreview.org/?p=318", "0", "post", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_a55jrcpgkb_posts` VALUES("359", "2", "2017-01-10 18:02:22", "2017-01-11 01:02:22", "[caption id=\"attachment_331\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-331\" src=\"http://hopkinsmedreview.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/A3_2-300x276.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"276\" /> I had to treat all kinds of turkeys with profound respect -said by Perri Klass, a medical student at Harvard Medical School[/caption]\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">When doctors go through medical school and residency, they are often victims of verbal abuse by medical superiors and are in medical settings that often call for doctors to detach themselves from their patients. Many believe that a culmination of these factors cause students to come out with significantly different moral values than those with which they initially came in with. These once aspiring students have more importantly become accustomed to a medical education system that has moved past teaching humanitarian values and has hyper-focused on STEM efforts. This has contributed to creating a generation of future doctors that will be less empathetic and more likely to abuse their own students and eventually, their own patients. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Students from the even the best medical schools fail to treat patients as people, as seen by Dr. Paul Kalanithis story </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">When Breath Becomes Air</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> (5). His story shows that students are simply so overwhelmed with work that they cant afford the time to feel feelings. They have to brush them aside and hope that these feelings will disappear by themselves. They lose themselves, wondering if they have made more moral slides than strides (5). When you have to witness so many deaths and tragedies, I believe that a certain amount of toughness is required in order to cope with the reality of the job. While I do recognize this, I also believe that the current medical education system is desensitizing the art of medicine far too much. The students have become desensitized to the point that in </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">When Breath Becomes Air</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, it was important enough for him to mention that although Dr. Kalanathi was unable to save the patient with severe head trauma, he was able to resuscitate his ice-cream sandwich (5). In </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Moral Education of Medical Students</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, it talks about how a doctor was amazing, yet abandoned the people that needed him but couldnt afford him (6). In both works, there is a recurring theme of doctors looking at patients as case reports rather than people. Ive heard of several incidents in which doctors dont know their patients names, even when the patient has essentially handed the fate of their life over to the doctor. Id question if my doctor would be willing to fight for my life if he didnt even take the effort to learn my name. Being emotionally detached is looked down upon but is still somewhat understandable. Being emotionally unavailable is unacceptable. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">I had to treat all kinds of turkeys with profound respect said by Perri Klass, a medical student at Harvard Medical School, in </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Patient-Centered Medicine: Transforming the Clinical Method</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> (1). Its apparent that many medical schools and programs are making students more robotic and less attached to their parents. Some argue that it is a necessity for the job and for this reason, we decided to talk to a medical student about this issue in hopes of learning more about the field. We got the opportunity to speak with Kevin Christopher, a 4th year medical student at the University of Cincinnati. He gave us some great advice in general and luckily gave us a great perspective of how students are treated in school and during rounds. Although it does vary occasionally, students are abused, victimized, and put in their place at alarming rates and even though preventative measures are tried, many are not effective in implementing any real change. He believes that doctors arent necessarily hardened by the toughness of the faculty; students just become meaner and more cutthroat in order to cope and survive in this medical culture. Exploitation by a medical superior wont help doctors strengthen up and wont assist them adjust to the realities of operating on their fellow human beings.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Kevin pointed out - something that I found very eye-opening and interesting - that a student will harden up no matter what in our system when they go into the medical field. When someone has witnessed so much morbidity in a matter of weeks, days, or even hours, they have a habit of putting up a shield in order to protect themselves. He emphasized that medical students harden up more because of medical school rather than physicians and elders. The medical education system is set up in a way to train students to be tough. These physicians often see their moral bearings decline as they progress with their medical education and a new study by (2) Evans et al. would say that the current medical forecast would put a focus on detachment and objective clinical neutrality. Doctors have focused on the drugs without considering the humanitarian part of medicine. As people that go to the hospital for when were sick or even for check ups, Im sure that most people would appreciate if doctors would be able to give advice that takes into account other variables that dont relate to purely medical factors. As a patient and a prospective medical student, I would be scared to hear that this is what the field has become. If I was being treated for a disease, I would much rather be seen as a person rather than a collection of statistics. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For any possibility of developing higher quality doctors, we would have to enact reform in the entire medical community. It would have to began at the undergraduate level. I believe medical schools should require one philosophy class for pre-medical students. Philosophy is the study of the general and fundamental problems in the world. Even a brief study of this can help premedical students think about medicine on a more holistic level rather than a field that is primarily STEM. Although philosophy, being the quest for truth while medicine is the quest for health, are in complementary ways striving for the enhancement of human wellbeing (4). A study by Marcus et al. (3) says that the technological aspects are currently the focus of the medical field rather than the humanitarian aspects to medicine. Philosophy can help medical students think from a more humanitarian perspective, which can give birth to a generation of new and innovative thinkers. After that, money should be invested in bringing a more humanitarian perspective into medical school. Students expect to learn about humans when they come to medical school, and rather than recognizing individual and societal needs, medical students only cover the human body. As mentioned earlier, the current medical forecast emphasizes detachment and objective clinical neutrality. By making students less stem oriented and more open to arts and humanities, theyll have a better understanding of the value of life, which will make them better doctors, and ultimately better people. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Before I started this paper, I firmly believed that the issue with the disconnect that students feel in the medical field was mostly attributed to abusive doctors and mentors. However, after looking into the issue and talking to medical professionals, I realized that this exploitation makes students more resentful and does not actually harden them up as some suggest they do. However, the entire medical field is set up in a way to make students toughen up and although I believe this is essential, its only to a degree. Humans need people to teach aspiring doctors in a professional and nurturing manner. Humans need doctors to be able to empathize with them in times of disparity. Humans need doctors to be human. </span>", "Make Doctors Human Again", "", "publish", "open", "open", "", "make-doctors-human-again", "", "", "2017-01-10 18:02:22", "2017-01-11 01:02:22", "", "0", "http://hopkinsmedreview.org/?p=320", "0", "post", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_a55jrcpgkb_posts` VALUES("360", "2", "2017-01-10 18:07:18", "2017-01-11 01:07:18", "<i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">By providing a venue for a free exchange of ideas, we plan on interviewing prominent scholars in the medical field who have contributed to the world with new perspectives to ideas. </span></i>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Today, we will be hearing from an Interventional Radiologist at the University of Rochester. </span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">I actually started medical school under the impression that I would join internal medicine, and this is actually because I had this preconceived notion of why I wanted to go to medical school, what kind of life or what kind of role I think I had as a doctor, and I really viewed it as being a primary care physician and having a lot of patient contact and being very close to my patients and involved with them. As a result, I really just assumed I would be an internist.</span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">So, I went on and pursued internal medicine, did my residency, and realized that I was basically surrounded by very unhappy people who were here for a variety of reasons. These people found it stressful, difficult to get grants, difficult to get research, and were kind of pulled into multiple different directions. I think they felt as if their jobs were never finished, and that there was always something they should be doing or could be doing better. </span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">A lot of my women colleagues and peers went into pediatrics or OBGYN. When I spoke to the chief of pediatrics at one of the hospitals I was worked at, I asked her about how to decide what specialty interests me. I asked her how she decided to choose her specialties. She told me that any student should look at the middle-aged people who are practicing their specialty that youre interested in and try to identify people that you really could relate to, people that you would like. If they were happy because you could relate to them and they seemed to be happy with what they were doing, then, that may be a good indicator that you would be happy.</span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">When I was in this residency and everybody that I worked with was miserable, I remembered what she said and thought to myself, I cant sign up for a lifetime of this. All the people that I like even seemed miserable and I didnt want to live like this.</span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">While all of this is happening, at the very same time, women still have all these expectations in addition to being the perfect doctor. Were supposed to be the perfect spouse and the perfect mother. After a certain point, there just arent enough hours in the day to do all of that. I was in a transition period in my life and I was thinking about my responsibilities to my family differently than when I was single.</span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">I found that it was stressful. Everything was stressful. I came back to the hospital and realized that it all came down to one thing: Who was happy. Some of the happiest physicians seemed to be radiologists. They were just happy people, they liked what they did, they liked to teach, and they seemed to relax, they were happy to talk to, and they werent stressed out all the time. I had no idea if I would be at all interested in it. I switched into radiology really because of what the pediatric chair said to me. I can see myself being the middle aged women radiologist.</span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">I changed from internal medicine to radiology really because I found medicine anxiety provoking. I found that many of people that did medicine were not happy and were frustrated, and I wanted something where I could control my hours better. I also wanted something that provided closure so that at the end of the day it was over so I could go home, turn it off, and do something else. Thats one of the great things about radiology. Each case is a problem, each case is a challenge, you finish it and move on to the next one.</span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Im part of the work and the diagnosis of many many patients and I feel like what I do is critically important in terms of helping a clinician come to a diagnosis so I feel like Im making a major contribution. Its interesting, the technology has evolved, and Im able to do research. On top of that, I learned that I had become a teacher. My residents and my medical students have replaced patients in some ways for me, and they are the people that I mentor, deal, and get close with and thats been incredibly rewarding for me.</span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;", "Editor\'s Pick: The Journey", "", "publish", "open", "open", "", "editors-pick-the-journey", "", "", "2017-01-17 15:51:26", "2017-01-17 22:51:26", "", "0", "http://hopkinsmedreview.org/?p=323", "0", "post", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_a55jrcpgkb_posts` VALUES("361", "5", "2017-01-10 18:08:13", "2017-01-11 01:08:13", "<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In just the past year, a lot has changed. David Bowie passed away. Donald Trump is our president-elect. Apple even came out with a new phone! Although the coverage on these issues have been massive and have certainly informed the American public, this coverage on the few has thrusted many other issues of massive significance onto the backburners. In fact, there has been minimal dialogue discussing one of the </span><b>biggest</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> public health problems of our time. </span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Now, before I delve into this issue, its important that I state this right from the get-go: I do not believe that it is necessary for universities to buy brand-name hygiene products and supply all of the students for their entire duration at the university. Although I would absolutely love to see such a thing happen, its important to note that this could become quite costly and discourage universities from even taking the first step at all. With that said, I do firmly believe that any and every student should have the right to access a high-quality tampon or a pad immediately if they ever need it, no matter what their gender, race, or socioeconomic standing is, whether it be due to an emergency or even affordability. The physical, social, and mental toll that people can suffer in not having access to these products right away is tremendous and by solving this issue from ever manifesting, students can avoid stress. </span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It has become high-time for colleges, whether it be their student government or administration, to protect the interest of their own students. Several schools have taken steps into the right direction; its now time for other schools to take up the mantle and truly ensure the health of their students. </span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;", "The New Movement", "", "publish", "open", "open", "", "the-new-movement", "", "", "2017-01-17 15:50:18", "2017-01-17 22:50:18", "", "0", "http://hopkinsmedreview.org/?p=325", "0", "post", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_a55jrcpgkb_posts` VALUES("362", "2", "2017-01-10 18:09:16", "2017-01-11 01:09:16", "<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">A doctor treats</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">A doctor heals</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">But does a doctor greet?</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Will the doctor feel?</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The doctor might treat, but who are they treating?</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The doctor sees the illness</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Not the person its defeating</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Everything has changed</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Before bills, medicine, and pills</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There was only a doctor and a patient</span></p>", "A Doctor and a Patient", "", "publish", "open", "open", "", "a-doctor-and-a-patient", "", "", "2017-01-17 15:44:16", "2017-01-17 22:44:16", "", "0", "http://hopkinsmedreview.org/?p=327", "0", "post", "", "0");
