INSERT INTO `wp_a55jrcpgkb_posts` VALUES("367", "1", "2017-01-17 15:52:31", "2017-01-17 22:52:31", "<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Medicine is the science or practice of the diagnosis, treatment, and prevention of disease</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. Doctors have great medical minds and are trained and licensed to treat sick and injured people. These Merriam-Webster definitions depicts what humans believe to be a doctors purpose. Meanwhile, death, by the very same dictionary, is defined as the ruin or destruction of something. The definitions of medicine and doctor have changed minimally over time. The definition of death, on the other hand, is one that reflects the modern attitude toward death, which incorporates aspects of Western and Judeo-Christian culture. With the advances in science and medicine, humans have become accustomed to taking advantage of the medical tools at their disposal, giving themselves a chance to extend their lives as much as possible. As a result, when death occurs, it is unexpected and disappointing to the family, the patient, and even the doctor. The process of death and dying in modern times places an economic burden on taxpayers and families. End of life care accounts for a sizable portion of our healthcare spending, which puts pressure on the government and grieving families. The culture and stigma in the United States surrounding death and dying is not only dangerous but unsustainable for Americans.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Death, as a construct, is scary. After all, a person that you may have known forever can vanish within a second. Yet, this construct of death is relatively new. In the past, death was much more foreseen and normalized. A national study looking into the perceptions of dying concluded that in the past and in eastern cultures, since death was much more predictable, it wasnt as threatening of a concept (5). With the shift towards chronic disease rather than infectious diseases and the rise of medicine and antibiotics, the idea that death is a part of life has become some sort of taboo. This stigma that is attached to death and dying remains because many believe that death will and can be delayed. Alongside the silent killers like heart disease, there are usually immediate causes of death that can be treated via medicine, which prolongs the death process. In Atul Gawandes book, Being Mortal, the slow killer is retinal disease, which was experienced by Bella, the geriatricians (Felix) wife. Felix had to retire from his job and completely support Bella after she went completely blind. As she continued to age, Bella lost large chunks of her memory and hearing. The quality of her life deteriorated to the point where Atul Gawande dared us to answer if it was even worth it for her to continue living like this (1). This pattern in medicine only results in spending large portions of a patients final year in the hospital circling the drain with low quality of life instead of spending time with their family at home. This pattern leads to another reason of why humans fear death more than they did in the past. In the duration of history, most deaths occurred at home (6). This means that relatives and family members were exposed to the experience of caring for dying people, which enabled them to have a first-hand experience with the dying process. </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">As a result, although death may have been just as tragic as it is today, it was also seen as more normal than the perception of death in more modern times. Since new therapeutic trials continue to flash in headlines and miracle cases are always trending, the American population has this notion of invincibility embedded into their thoughts (3). Thus, when death is imminent, people are more willing to try drastic, high-risk, low-reward measures which often yield in unfortunate circumstances. Unfortunately, these tactics place an economic strain on citizens, hospitals, and the government.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The healthcare system in America is tough for even the best hospitals, and the worst is yet to come as costs continue to rise and the baby boomer generation continues to age. End-of-life care is among some of the costliest government expenditures. On average, Medicare paid about $26,000 on average for the last year of a persons life. In fact, end-of-life care allots for approximately 10 to 12% of total healthcare spending (4). This type of spending begs us to ask a question: why is so much money going into end-of-life care spending? Objectively speaking, about 10% of taxpayer dollars in the healthcare sector is washed down the drain in end of life care since the patients life ends within a year anyway. The current Medicare system in the US is unsustainable and makes it almost impossible to continue practicing medicine this way (4). </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Currently, there are 34.8 million Americans that are above the age of 65. This figure will double by 2050 to about 72.2 million. On top of that, there will be an expected 240% increase in the 85-plus population (2). With this increased dependency ratio and newfound dependence on the working class supporting their elders, it is simply economically unfeasible to expect our taxpayers pick up the tab for this populations Medicare and insurance. It would require drastic tax hikes and would put much pressure on those who are employed to produce for the those who have low survival chances (4).</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">These expenses dont even factor in what the family must contribute for the medical bills. Although Medicare does cover many aspects of healthcare, there are many treatments and drugs that are unreasonably expensive, even for people with coverage (3). Families are responsible for paying their share, which could be thousands of dollars in medical bills, even if the treatment doesnt work and this could end up being money flushed down the toilet (3). A possible solution that balances longevity of life while being economically practical could be cutting off benefits after they reach the average age of death in the country. For example, if a senior citizen was possibly getting Medicare, she would get the full benefits of Medicare until the age of 78, which is the average death of an America. After that, she would still receive coverage, however, there would be more limitations to prevent the waste of money. Although in an ideal world, it would be incredible for no one to die, it is not realistic and this train of thought can prove to be harmful to everyone. </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Spending loads of taxpayer money for end-of-life care should not be necessary and massive reform must occur to address unsustainable culture of Americas healthcare system.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Although Merriam Webster defines death as the ruin or destruction of something, it has become evident that this definition needs a reboot, which would also call for the restructuring of an entire culture. Whether it be due to the immediateness of death or the emotions attached to death and dying, the concept of death needs to be redefined, particularly in America. While other cultures have accepted or even celebrated death, Western culture has treated death like a taboo, despite it being something that every human being on this planet will go through. With the unfeasible culture of end-of-life care spending and the emotional withdrawal attached to dying, we can no longer afford this definition of death. If there was one phrase that I took from reading Being Mortal, it was this: In the end, people dont view their life as merely the average of all of its moments- which, after all, is mostly nothing much plus some sleep. For human beings, life is meaningful because it is a story. A story has a sense of a whole, and its arc is determined by the significant moments, the ones where something happens. The definition of death is no longer the ruin or destruction of something; in reality, its simply the last phase of the life cycle, one that helps write the conclusion to a humans story.</span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;", "Death Magnified", "", "inherit", "closed", "closed", "", "358-revision-v1", "", "", "2017-01-17 15:52:31", "2017-01-17 22:52:31", "", "358", "http://hopkinsmedreview.org/358-revision-v1/", "0", "revision", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_a55jrcpgkb_posts` VALUES("368", "1", "2017-01-17 15:53:10", "2017-01-17 22:53:10", "<i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">My kids. My husband. What would they do without me. </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">I woke up in cold sweat, writhing in pain. My stomach was on fire and every few minutes, I had to go to the restroom. It was 4 in the morning, my kids were fast asleep, and my husband was overseas. This acute pain has occurred several times but something was different today. Something was wrong. I suffered through dawn until the sun rose and then I quickly got the kids ready and dropped them off at school.Afterwards I booked it straight to the local clinic. I lucked out with the take-a-number and got number 64, which meant that Id be allowed to see the doctor that day and that the wait would only be for a few hours. I sat in my seat, fearing that I would have to pay for the brand name medicine that they would prescribe, causing me to miss out on a lunch or two. The issue couldnt have been bad since I have been the epitome of good health. Ive done everything I could to avoid problems in general. Despite being an African American mother with a husband overseas, I was doing incredibly well for myself. Id had my high school diploma for a while and even passed my army entrance exam. After coming back from my station in Germany, I was pregnant with my first daughter, Semaj. I swore that I wouldnt let her experience the childhood that I had to go through. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">After four hours, my number was called. I sat down in the room, waited 30 more minutes for the doctor to show up and was privileged a grand total of 5 minutes. He asked me for my name, quickly chatted me up, asked me where the pain was, and went on to do his medical talk. He said it was a simple stomachache and if I took the medication he prescribed, itd get all better. So I went home, took my meds every 4 hours, and waited for the pain to subside. I waited for a week until the pain had rendered me useless. It was impossible for me to even get out of bed, forget about going to work. I went back to the clinic and requested to be checked as soon as possible. After a two-hour wait, the same doctor came by and looked at my case. He once again, asked me for my name, talked to me for a few seconds, looked at where the pain was, and went to work. This time, he told me that the issue I have is out of his area of expertise. After all, the clinic didnt have a stomach doctor, just an internal medicine 4</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">th</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> year resident working here to log in his clinic hours. I got mad. Very mad. I was skeptical at first, and thought that he was a prick that didnt want to treat an uneducated, black lady. There was an article in my favorite newspaper, Atlanta Black Star, called 7 Ways Black People Are Mistreated by Doctors and Hospitals which talked about how white doctors dont like black patients (3) . The doctor pulled out some medical paper called the \"Comparison of a community clinic with a hospital out-patient clinic in rheumatology and started talking about how clinics dont have money because of some government gibberish which is why the quality of care in clinics is lower than that of a hospital (2). He also claimed that these test were too expensive, but I didnt trust him (2). Ive dealt with discrimination my whole life and I wasnt planning on letting the likes of him take advantage of me. I wasnt going to leave the clinic until he wrote me a referral to the hospital. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The next week, I went to the hospital the internist had referred me too and met with a nice young gastroenterologist, Dr. Burke, who put me through several tests. After a few days of testing and a waiting period to see the results, she told me that I something called chronic painful inflammation of the GI tract. I was relieved. I had thought that this issue could last years but it sounded temporary. After all, Ive had inflammation on my knees before and its never been more than a minor inconvenience. Just as I was getting ready to do my victory dance, the doctor quickly destroyed any and all happiness I had by telling me that this issue could be persistent for years and that I should be in bed for the next two months. Despite killing all of my joy, this doctor performed their job significantly better than the internist. She consoled and sympathized with me, and even went as far to tell me that she would pay for a week worth of medicine. Dr. Burke knew that I was having trouble with the bills and changed out one of my more expensive medicines for a cheaper alternative. She understood that my kids were starting to feel my pain, so she sat with me and helped me talk through my issues. She even informed her next patient that she would be seeing them late. Right before she had to leave, Dr. Burke also referred me to her friend, Dr. Jones, who ended up being someone I could talk to about my issues. Dr. Jones was the director of Healthy African American Families II. Anyways, Dr. Burke finally prescribed the medicine to me and I was on my way of taking three pills a day for two months. As I slowly started registering what had happened, everything hit me. How could all this happen to me? How was I expected to leave this cycle of poverty? How am I just going to stay above water? </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The next day, I requested a leave of absence from my job. I soon lost my income and the money that my husband was sending just wasnt enough to support a family of three. I had lost my savings and everything that I had worked for in the last 23 years. Over the next four years, rather than working, I became a chauffeur. The only issue was that I didnt have a car since mine broke down. Oh, and I didnt get paid. Instead, I spent 5 dollars a day, which was out of my budget, to spend 6 hours on a public bus to drop off and pick up my kids. I didnt have enough money to pay for my prescriptions at all times so I often split the medicine in half or skipped it altogether whenever the pain was tolerable. In fact, my friend who was a medical assistant read somewhere that 3.8 billion prescriptions are written every year yet only 50% are ever taken correctly or taken at all (4). If only 50% of the patient population was taken their meds properly, why did I have to hold myself to such a high standard? I decided thatd it be fine to skip my dose once or twice. Dr. Burke always claimed it was dangerous and even though I trusted her, I couldnt bring myself to ask for more free drugs. Not taking the medicine once here and there wouldnt make much of a difference. Eventually, I had to move out of my big house and start living in what was essentially a shoebox. With the constant stress of living in such a dangerous environment, traveling back and forth to drop off my kids, and having no steady source of money, my life started closing in on me. In fact, I realized that life shouldnt be this hard and if it didnt want me, I shouldnt be here. I was placed in a ward for a short time to stabilize, but when I got out, life went on as it had for the last 4 years. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">I always hear chatter of people saying that if you work hard enough, you can become anything or go anywhere. I dont believe this is true. I had several issues with how my life played out in the last 4 years. Not receiving disability aid for my obvious disability made it almost impossible to get out of this cycle of poverty. The court told me to get a lawyer to represent me, yet they didnt even understand that I have trouble buying a bus ticket on a daily basis. How do I plan on hiring a lawyer? The crazy thing was, the government didnt help me find a lawyer. They didnt provide support of any kind. All I had was my welfare for a family of three, which might buy us a few lunches and dinners but what about utilities? How about rent? The structure of the economic system in America coupled with governmental policies makes it very hard for people like me to break out of the cycle of poverty. My socioeconomic position was of no assistance to me either. My race and gender put me at a disadvantage in numerous ways. I came from a poor family to begin with and I was one of the first to finally get out of this cycle until injury took my job and my money. This all started factoring into my own health. Taking care of my kids took a big toll on my body. Its not as if I didnt want to make sure my kids succeeded, but it came at a cost. I had simply become my childrens servant, dropping them off, picking them up, and most importantly, keeping them on track. My house was a mess and the doctors were always yelling at me for not taking my medicine. They didnt understand that I didnt have the luxury of buying all of my medicine. I was always anxious, suffered from depression, and even experienced suicidal thoughts. Dr. Burke was there, but even then, I only saw her once every 4 months. I did everything a human could do. It just wasnt enough</span>", "The Pre-Mortem Biography of the Cycle of Poverty", "", "inherit", "closed", "closed", "", "353-revision-v1", "", "", "2017-01-17 15:53:10", "2017-01-17 22:53:10", "", "353", "http://hopkinsmedreview.org/353-revision-v1/", "0", "revision", "", "0");
